The Disir summon King Arthur to receive the judgement of the Triple Goddess and Arthur decides to respond. All does not go as planned, and the King and his knights' recklessness leave Mordred gravely wounded. Desperate, Arthur decides to petition the Disir for help and him and Merlin seek them out again. The Disir give Arthur an ultimatum: embrace magic, or the Triple Goddess will seal his fate against him. Merlin seizes what he sees as the opportunity to kill Mordred and reminds Arthur that there is no place for magic in Camelot. The Disir seal Arthur's fate and when he returns, Mordred is well again. Merlin realises only then what happened; in not embracing magic, Arthur sealed his fate; Mordred lives.

data: A stew of tomato, onion, garlic, red pepper and rabbit, thickened with cake flour.
A stew made of beef braised in red wine, traditionally red Burgundy, and beef broth, generally flavoured with garlic, onions and a bouquet garni, with pearl onions and mushrooms.
A stew made from long chilies, coconut milk, shrimp paste or stockfish, onion, pork, and garlic.
A meat stew that features white cabbage, sauerkraut, various cuts of meat and sausages, often whole or puréed tomatoes, honey and mushrooms as ingredients.
Typical Bosnian dish with ingredients: beef, lamb, cabbage, potatoes, tomatoes, carrots, parsley, garlic and peppercorns (whole, not ground).

A tomato-based stew containing various types of lima beans/butter beans, corn, okra, and other vegetables, and one or more types of meat. Most recipes claiming authenticity call for squirrel or rabbit meat, but chicken, pork, and beef are also common ingredients.
A fish stew with several different types of fish and shellfish cooked in wine, tomatoes, and chili pepper.
English:Galician stew. It is made with fatty pork, white beans and greens (cabbage or spring greens)
A stew made from long chilies, coconut milk, shrimp paste or stockfish, onion, pork, and garlic.
A vegetable and meat stew of chuños, onions, carrots, potatoes, white corn, beef and wheat kernels.
The ciambotta is based on vegetables, but may have other ingredients such as meat or fish. The vegetable choices are usually potatoes, eggplant, tomatoes, peppers, chilli, onion and herbs.
A regional style of Chili con carne characterized by the use of unusual seasonings such as cinnamon, cloves, allspice or chocolate.
A classic Provençal stew made with inexpensive beef braised in wine, vegetables, garlic, and herbes de Provence, and traditionally cooked in a daubière, a braising pan.
A stew made with various combinations of meat, potatoes, onions, vegetables, and sometimes fruits.

A Filipino savory stew of meat and/or offal (typically lungs, kidneys, intestines, ears, heart and snout) simmered in a rich, spicy dark gravy of pig blood, garlic, chili (most often siling mahaba), and vinegar.
Stewed tripe, with curry, fennel, monosodium glutamate and salt.

A vegetable stew made with beef, olives, tomatoes, mushrooms, rice, onions, herbs, and spices and is often served with "Balkan mixed salad", a combination of roasted eggplant, sweet peppers, garlic, tomatoes, and vinegar.

A thick, tart stew made from pomegranate juice and ground walnuts that is traditionally made with poultry, but variants using balls of ground meat, ghormeh cut lamb, fish, or no meat at all are not unusual.
A meat stew with common ingredients including beef tripe, beef, bay leaf, parsley, carrot, beef broth, and spices to taste, including salt, black pepper, nutmeg, sweet paprika, and marjoram.

A dish that consists of potatoes, onions, and whatever meat was available, cooked in a stew and topped with dumplings. The common meats used were chicken (fricot au poulet), clams (fricot aux coques), rabbit (fricot au lapin des bois), beef, or pork.
A dish that consist of a mixture of sautéed herbs, consisting mainly of parsley, leek, and a smaller amount of fenugreek leaves—where this is usually the dry herb of the mix.
A soup or stew of meat, noodles and vegetables (especially potato), seasoned with paprika and other spices.

Pepperpot is a stewed meat dish, strongly flavored with cinnamon, hot peppers, and Cassareep, a special sauce made from the Cassava root. Beef, pork, and mutton are the most popular meats used, though some have been known to use chicken.
A traditional Dutch stew based on diced meat, fish or bird, and vegetables.
A traditional German stew made from marinated rabbit or hare, cut into stewing-meat sized pieces and braised with onions and wine in a marinade thickened with the animal's blood.
A thick stew made from pemmican (a mix of dried meat, fat, and cereal) or other meat, thickener such as ground biscuits, and water.
A traditional stew made from lamb, or mutton as well as potatoes, carrots, onions, and parsley.
A stew whose main ingredients are beans, sauerkraut, potatoes, bacon, spare ribs, and the main seasoning is garlic.
A spicy stew whose thick gravy is based on chickpea flour (called Besan in Hindi) and contains vegetable fritters called pakoras, to which sour yoghurt is added to give it little sour taste.
A famous dish whose common ingredients are goat shoulders with tomato paste and liver spread.
A popular stew made from peanut sauce with a variety of vegetables, stewed oxtail, beef, and occasionally offal or tripe. Meat variants may include goat meat or (rarely) chicken.

A stew that features a combination of pork and beef, but lamb can also be used. The hot pot is usually seasoned with black peppercorns and salt. Other seasonings such as allspice and bay leaf may be used too. Common vegetables such as carrot, onion, and root vegetables are acceptable additions to the stew.
A cooked stew consisting of various meats simmered in a broth with a buckwheat flour based pudding.
A dish made traditionally from lamb or mutton and onion, topped with sliced potatoes, left to bake in the oven all day in a heavy pot and on a low heat.
A thick vegetable stew which features peppers and tomato, onion, lard, salt, sugar and ground paprika as a base recipe.

A hearty thick stew whose main ingredients are corn, some form of meat (usually beef, but sometimes beef jerky or chorizo), and vegetables. Other ingredients vary widely, and typically include onion, beans, squash or pumpkin.
A dish consisting of stewed sheep's head, with curry, fennel, monosodium glutamate and salt.
A stew that is made from lamb, beef or chicken and is cooked with a sauce based on tomato and groundnuts (peanuts).
A dish of stewed beans, tomatoes and onion.
A dish made from cow's feet, stewed with beans and vegetables.
A South Indian stew with coconut and lentils as a base.
A French ragoût (stew) of lamb or mutton. Often, vegetables are added.
Ndolé is the national dish of Cameroon that consists of a stew of nuts, ndoleh (bitter leaves indigenous to West Africa), and fish or ground beef.
A stew that is primarily made from chicken mixed with a thick tomato sauce.

A typical stew that is usually made of a shellfish stock containing different kinds of cooked shellfish and fish. These are complemented with a variety of herbs and spices such as garlic, cilantro, onion.
A hot stew of chopped-up baked unleavened bread cooked in lamb broth and served with lamb meat. It is often eaten with pickled garlic and chilli sauce.
A famous German stew that consists of several types of meats and vegetables. Common ingredients are beef, pork and mutton as well as potatoes, carrots and leek.
A Filipino stew made of taro leaves, chilli, meat and coconut milk wrapped in gabi leaves and tied securely with coconut leaf.
A worldwide known French beef stew. Other ingredients may differ from region to region but commonly various kinds of vegetables are included such as carrots, turnips, leeks, celery and onions.

A South African stew that is usually prepared outside. The recipe commonly contains meat, vegetables, starches like rice or potatoes, all slow-cooked with Dutch-Malay spices, the distinctive spicing of South Africa's early culinary melting pot. Other common ingredients include fruits and flour-based products like pasta.

A thick soup or stew made by boiling vegetables, grains, and, if available, meat or fish.Pottage commonly consisted of various ingredients easily available to serfs and peasants and could be kept over the fire for a period of days, during which time some of it was eaten and more ingredients added. The result was a dish that was constantly changing.
A Mexican stew with ritual significance made from maize with meat, usually pork, chicken, turkey, pork rinds, chili peppers, and other seasonings and garnish.Vegetarian and vegan versions also exist.
A stew of mutton chops, made with flour, shredded wheat, chillies, dry curd cheese, water and salt.

A famous vegetable stew from the Provence that consists mainly of tomatoes with garlic, onions, courgettes (zucchini), aubergine (eggplant), poivron (bell peppers), marjoram and basil, or bay leaf and thyme, or a mix of green herbs like herbes de Provence.
A stew made using potatoes (pottu, peruna), some pork and the main ingredient, so-called "rössy" i.e. blood pudding made of blood, beer, rye flour and some spices.

A basic stew or porridge consumed by 'coureurs des bois' and 'voyageurs' (fur traders) and Métis people of North America, traditionally made of peas or corn (or both) with grease (bear or pork) and a thickening agent (bread or flour).
A native-American stew made from hominy or Indian corn. Additional ingredients varyingly include vegetables, wild rice, brown sugar, animal fat, beans, smoked fish or animal brains.
A spicy stew made from minced pork or dog meat (or more rarely, water buffalo meat) stewed in blood, coconut milk and spices.
A type of meat stew that is processed in thick brown gravy. The main material used in semur gravy is shallots, onions, garlic, kecap manis (sweet soy sauce), nutmeg and cloves.
A homogenous stew whose primary ingredient is powdered chickpeas or broad bean meal.
A Filipino soup or stew characterized by its sour flavor most often associated with tamarind (sampalok).
An Irish stew made from pork and pork kidneys.
A cowboy dish consisting of whatever is on hand. Most recipes call for meat and offal from a calf.

A traditional dish from North Carolina and Georgia. It is a type of stew consisting of parboiled whole chicken in a cream or milk based broth, butter and seasoned with salt, pepper and other ingredients. Traditionally, the stew is served in the late fall and winter months.

A Berber dish from North Africa, that is named after the special earthenware pot in which it is cooked. Includes different ingredients according to region, but commonly several kinds of vegetables and spices]]
A traditional Welsh stew, made with smoked bacon, stock, potatoes and other vegetables.
A dish made of pieces of bread in vegetable or meat broth. Pictured is lamb tharid.
A South African stew with Dutch origin that usually features mutton, is cooked for a very long time, and includes cinnamon, cardamom, ginger, cloves and chili as seasonings.

A traditional vegetable stew that contains layers of sliced potatoes, aubergines and red bell peppers previously fried in olive oil. The aubergines and red peppers should not be peeled. The whole is topped with tomato fried with garlic and parsley and presented in a way that it looks like a pie without a crust.
A stew or curry which may be prepared with chicken, beef, lamb, a variety of vegetables, and spice mixtures such as berbere and niter kibbeh, a seasoned clarified butter.

Literally means 'small water flower stew' in English (comes from Afrikaans). It is made of meat, typically lamb, stewed together with the waterblommetjies (Aponogeton distachyos flowers, commonly known as Cape pondweed, Cape hawthorn or Cape asparagus)
The stew is made of the fish or chicken, vegetables including carrots, leeks and potatoes, herbs, eggs, cream and butter.
A stew made with poultry giblets and possibly the head, feet and wing tips.
A stew made of caparrón, a variety of red kidney bean, and a spicy sausage chorizo.
A stew made with different meats and vegetables, numerous regional variations exist throughout Portugal and Spain.

A stew whose main ingredient is the chickpea or garbanzo bean, preferably of its larger variety (also known as kabuli). Vegetables are added: potatoes mainly, but also cabbage, carrots, and turnips. In some cases, green bean, mangold and cardoon is also added.

A stew that contains a pilota, a very big meatball spiced with garlic and parsley; it also contains vegetables as celery, cabbage, carrots, etc. depending on the season. Additionally, bones, sausages called botifarras, and other types of meat, can be used.

Fabada is made with dried large white beans (fabes de la Granja, soaked overnight before use), shoulder of pork (Lacón Gallego) or bacon (tocino), black pudding (morcilla), chorizo, and often saffron (azafrán). Some recipes also call for longaniza.
A clam stew that calls for small clams, fava beans, onions, garlic, salt, saffron, bay leaves, olive oil, parsley, bread crumbs and sometimes sweet paprika.
A typical Basque dish prepared with onion, green peppers, and tomatoes sautéd and flavoured with red Espelette pepper.
A stew made of tomatoes, onions, eggplant or courgettes, green and red peppers and olive oil.
A fish stew that was eaten on tuna fishing boats in the Cantabrian Sea. Today it is a beautiful and simple dish with potatoes, onions, pimientos, and tomatoes.
A stew of ham with cabbage and other vegetables, usually with cheese and stale bread added.
A stew made from lobster which is added to a sofrito, onion, tomato, garlic and parsley and boiled, and is eaten with thin slices of bread.
A Spanish stew made from pork and beans and an inconsistent, wide variety of other meats and vegetables, often including chickpeas, depending on the recipe used.
A stew based in boiling vegetables and meat in a casserole.
